Here is a shader code to saturate half flops on a RDNA2 GPU using the built-in saturate instruction:


```csharp
#pragma surf Lambertian lighting
sampler2D sceneColor = _Tex2D(_SceneColorHandle, _CameraPositionHandle);
float2 halfway = _CameraPositionHandle * 0.5;
float3 sceneLight(float2 uv) {
    float lightValue = sceneColor[halfway];
    float distance = length(uv - halfway);
    float ambient = lightValue * 0.6;
    float brightness = lightValue * 0.4;
    float intensity = pow(distance, 2.0) * brightness;
    float2 saturatedValue = _Saturate(intensity);
    return float4(sceneLight.rgb, sceneLight.a);
}

```

In this code, we first import the `` surf `` directive to enable surface shading. We then declare a sampler2D variable called `` sceneColor `` to hold the color of the scene at the camera position. We also define `` halfway `` as a `` float2 `` that holds the coordinates of the halfway point between the near clip and far clip planes.

In the `` sceneLight() `` function, we first calculate the value of the `` sceneColor `` variable at the halfway point between the near clip and far clip planes. We then calculate the ambient, brightness, and intensity of the light using the `` pow() `` function.

Finally, we use the `` _Saturate() `` function from the RDNA 2 saturate instructions to saturate the intensity value between 0 and 1 to get the final light value.

Note that we use the `` float2 saturatedValue `` variable to store the saturated value, which is a 2D value that holds the saturated intensity value between 0 and 1.

